<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague – Dresden motorway Preliminary remark Without trans-European motorways, the modern, united Europe could only cope with the high volume of traffic between the partner countries with considerable restrictions and quality losses.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are essential for maintaining and increasing living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economic passenger and freight transport is an important task for the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a high degree of organizational, technical and financial effort.</seg>
<seg id="7">The establishment and development of a sustainable European transport infrastructure often requires difficult compromises with European and national policy objectives, such as the preservation of the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">It is precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures that the construction of the transport infrastructure is time-consuming.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and awarding the construction of transport routes, administrations can, through careful action and decision-making, save considerable financial resources and use them for other useful purposes.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state auditing authorities is to identify defects that stand in the way of optimum cost-effectiveness, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness in spending on the construction of transport facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit authorities should not only draw the attention of administrations to the shortcomings that have been identified, but also propose improvements for the benefit of citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Bundesrechnungshof (BRH) and the Nejvyi kontrolnad (NK), carried out parallel audits of the expenditure for the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and motorway A 17 in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The two motorways are connected by a border bridge jointly financed by both states.</seg>
<seg id="15">The co-operation with the NKE enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth assessment of the cost-effectiveness of the use of funds in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the course of the cooperation with the BRH, the NKx received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">In line with the planning progress, the date of completion was finally set for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">During the award procedure, however, the Road and Highway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made mistakes that delayed the procedure and shortened the available construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor secured the accelerated construction of the bridge until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">For this, however, the RMD had to accept considerable additional costs.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit activity, the prices of motorway bridges on the D 8 and the A 17 were compared. The benchmark for the price comparison of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge under the large bridges with lengths of over 100 m was the most expensive.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the increase in prices as a result of delays in awarding contracts.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices of the tunnels showed that the prices of the tunnels in the course of the D 8 are considerably higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">In future audits of the cost-effectiveness of transport infrastructure expenditure, both BRH as well as NKE can rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both audit offices recommend standardizing bridge constructions and carrying out steel composite and special constructions only where reinforced concrete constructions are unsuitable.</seg>
<seg id="30">The test process was characterized by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel examination, the examiners from both sides exchanged their expertise and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of this report is the parallel testing of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The focus of the audit was on cost-effectiveness, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel tests were carried out by the BRH in Germany and the National Chamber of Commerce in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="36">in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">It examined the economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of expenditure on the borderline section 0807 of the D8 motorway, amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion gross (approx. EUR 690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, EUR 64 million will be made available from EU Structural Funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">The BRH had already examined the planning and construction of the A17 motorway in the years 2003 to 2005 independently of the parallel tests with the NK.</seg>
<seg id="40">Of the financial volume for the construction of all three sections of the A 17 of approximately 670 million euros, 277 million euros will be co-financed by European Funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague – Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Corridor IV Dresden – Central and Southeastern Europe – Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech/German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">the A 17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the test, the border sections of the motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 on the Czech side remains incomplete, since the section 0805 over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">Here the crossing of a protected landscape area in the Bohemian Central Mountains is planned.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the traffic volume in 2008 in the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway will amount to 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the volume of traffic on the A 17 at the Czech border in 2010 to be around 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic signed an agreement to merge the German A17 motorway and the Czech D8 motorway on the common state border by erecting a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both states are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction measure represented an important aspect of the parallel audits of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NK</seg>
<seg id="53">From mid-2005, the two courts of auditors jointly considered cooperation in the examination of the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is partly financing the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech Road Administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no possibility for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">In order to be able to assess whether the funds were used sparingly with regard to the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8, the NKx had no comparative data at its disposal.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">It also had to check the effectiveness of the expenditure. To this end, the essential technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels should be examined, which should ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">After preparatory negotiations, the presidents of the two courts of auditors closed on 04. January 2006 an agreement on the coordination of the tests of the motorway Prague – Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="64">The auditors of both audit institutions met in the course of 2006 at about six to eight-week intervals.</seg>
<seg id="65">They dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for checking bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results for the construction of the border bridge and produced joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">A key aspect of the cooperation was the ongoing exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH mainly focused on the comparison of the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels as well as the procurement procedures, the NKO mainly developed the methodology for the analysis of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs, and so does the way in which the two audit bodies complete their audits.</seg>
<seg id="69">For this reason, both authorities drew up separate national reports on their audit results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel tests.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation ends with the signing of a final communique in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge as far as possible in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">Later they postponed the appointment by mutual agreement until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as the client of the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany is co-financing 42.13% of the bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD provided for a prestressed concrete construction for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, however, the RMD and its German partner agreed on the construction of a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision with the possible reduction of the number of pairs of pillars from seven to five and the associated environmental benefits for the Talaue.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had identified the steel composite construction as the more cost-effective solution.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, this was based on a calculation error.</seg>
<seg id="82">The calculation was based on a length of the new steel composite construction of only 397 m,</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, however, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award procedure, the RMD made serious mistakes,</seg>
<seg id="85">by insufficiently preparing the award documents and describing both evaluation criteria and sub-criteria inaccurately.</seg>
<seg id="86">These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments by the Evaluation Commission and the Director General of the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="87">An inferior bidder contested the outcome of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">The subsequent investigation by the Czech Antitrust Office delayed the signing of the construction contract for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="89">As a result, the summer construction season following the offer test was lost in 2004 and the total construction time available was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in less time. This led to a significant price increase.</seg>
<seg id="91">The measures offered included the double assembly of the superstructures, the modification of the pillar shape and the construction of an assembly hall.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the originally planned steel grade.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel – the higher costs of which were borne by the client alone – made it possible to shorten the construction time intended for corrosion protection and thus the total construction time.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the offer price of approx. EUR 18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and further additions will significantly increase the total construction costs of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction period alone led to a price increase of around ’5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">The costs are currently approx. 25.9 million euros net (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of the prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">Both audit offices examined the bridge prices on the D 8 and the A 17 in order to identify the bridges, which were characterized by particularly high prices and to compare the bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The study was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German motorways A 71, A 38 and A 4, as there were no comparable tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="101">In the preparation of this part of the examination, a precise definition of the concept of price was important.</seg>
<seg id="102">For the comparison of bridge prices, both courts of auditors agreed on detailed specifications, for example: to use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.</seg>
<seg id="103">(The VAT rates in the Czech Republic and Germany are different and may change), not to take into account the costs of special start-up measures, to use the exchange rate of the European Central Bank of 30.12.2005 for the currency conversion. (29 CZK - 1 euro).</seg>
<seg id="104">Bridges of different types (steel concrete, reinforced concrete, steel composite and steel) and different sizes are available on both the D 8 and the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the comparability of the tested bridge structures, the bridges were grouped according to their design.</seg>
<seg id="106">The analyses also took into account the bridge size within these groups.</seg>
<seg id="107">The most common were concrete bridges on both sides of the border (20 bridges on the D 8 and 36 bridges on the A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The study focused on this type of bridge, as the size of the sample allowed the application of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The study showed that the m2 price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 / A 17 depends on the bridge size (length, road surface): the larger the bridge, the lower the square meter price.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the correlation between price and size is more pronounced than for Czech bridges (see illustrations below).</seg>
<seg id="111">On the A 17 two bridges could be identified, on the D 8 four bridges with a significantly increased price.</seg>
<seg id="112">These bridges were determined partly by a method for determining significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (based on the distance to the regression curve, atypically expensive bridges can be identified).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, the atypically high price of these bridges should only serve as an indication of which bridges to focus on.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw final conclusions, the causes for the respective high price have to be determined in individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="115">This could be due, for example, to uneconomic administrative action, but also to the requirements for the protection of the environment or other legitimate reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Taking into account the larger average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to the German ones (see Table 1), the proven negative correlation between the bridge price and the length indicated that the Czech concrete bridges are cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">This was also supported by lower labour costs in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">However, the evaluation of the results showed that the price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 is higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During joint meetings, two reasons for this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, construction contracts for bridges are predominantly awarded separately.</seg>
<seg id="122">This also enables medium-sized companies to participate in the award competition.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridge constructions are awarded as part of larger contracts for the construction of several kilometers of motorway sections.</seg>
<seg id="124">Orders of this size cannot be handled by medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, the variety of bridge constructions built is greater than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the NKE noted that the construction of bridges will be determined long before construction begins,</seg>
<seg id="128">already at the time of the submission of the application for planning approval by the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, it selects a specific bridge construction variant from several alternatives. However, economic efficiency plays a subordinate role in this decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">Only through a thorough analysis of the construction sectors of both countries would a final conclusion have been possible with regard to bridge prices in the Czech Republic and Germany. However, this would have blown up the scope of this examination.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive steel composite bridge on the D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">The prices for the tunnels on the D 8 are about twice as high as in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the technical parameters between the tunnels on the D 8 and the tunnels in Germany showed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">The significant price differences can be the result of an underdeveloped competition for tunnel constructions in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow general conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Economic efficiency and effectiveness of the Dresden – Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was founded in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government adopted the plan for the expansion of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The plan was to gradually expand the D8 from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">The section 0805 was to be built by the Bohemian Central Mountains in front of the border section 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic finances the D8 under the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In the program number 327 220 “Construction of the motorway D 8 Prague – "st" nad Labem – Czech German state border" two objectives are defined:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">as a national objective: to improve the link between Prague and the Oesti nad Labem;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">as an international destination: the connection between Prague and Berlin as part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV BerlinIstanbul.</seg>
<seg id="147">The programme provided for the completion of the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains in June 2008 and the construction of the border section 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be noted that the end of the construction work is not identical with the time of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">For the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains, the NKE noted that the planning approval decision had already been issued.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental associations have brought an action against this decision.</seg>
<seg id="151">A final verdict is still pending.</seg>
<seg id="152">Compared to the timetable provided for in the programme documentation, a delay in the completion of section No.0805 could not be ruled out for several years.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed a postponement of the completion date of the construction phase No.0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national goal of improving the connection between Prague and Usti nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD underwent an economic analysis of section no. 0807 of the D 8 near the border and section no.0805 of the Bohemian Central Mountains between 1999 and 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">As an investment cost, it invested around 639 million euros for both sections No. 0805 and No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the Economic Performance Survey (EIRR)</seg>
<seg id="158">Variant opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 18 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="160">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 22 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="162">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 25 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic feasibility study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section close to the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains would go under traffic at the same time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The costs of both sections as at 31.12.2005 amounted to 897 million euros without VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the cost-effectiveness assessment of 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">In addition, there is a risk that Section 0805 will get another more elaborate in-service course, which would affect the economic viability of the project.</seg>
<seg id="169">The cost-effectiveness analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010 is economically justified.The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="170">However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains assumes a traffic volume of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the cost-effectiveness limit.</seg>
<seg id="171">Higher traffic volumes on the routes, which are intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains, are highly likely to result in traffic jams and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original cost-effectiveness study.</seg>
<seg id="172">The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">The construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.</seg>
<seg id="174">Cost increases also occurred in the construction of the A 17 as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the macroeconomic assessment for the Federal Transport Infrastructure Plan 1992, the Federal Ministry responsible for transport assumed investment costs of around 320 million euros.</seg>
<seg id="176">It thus determined a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, the costs have increased to around 670 million euros and the benefit/cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A17 motorway, regardless of the parallel tests with the NK.</seg>
<seg id="179">He noted that the authority responsible for the permit required an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the course of the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the road construction administration of the superfluousness of the landscape tunnel.</seg>
<seg id="181">As a result, 10 million euros in construction costs and 150,000 euros in annual operating costs could be avoided.</seg>
<seg id="182">During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction project was insufficiently prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">In the planning phase, the road construction administration refrained from recording the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall, as it was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">Only when the tunnel propulsion reached the wall did it catch up.</seg>
<seg id="186">It turned out that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Extensive measures such as anchorages, injections and stone impact protection nets for around 3.3 million euros were necessary.</seg>
<seg id="188">The road construction administration not only bore the costs for additional, already necessary services such as securing the Dölzschener wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary for a perfect construction preparation.</seg>
<seg id="189">These include expenses due to disturbed construction processes (3.2 million euros), additional training of the tunnelling team (0.5 million euros) and increased wages and material prices due to the construction time extension (7 million euros).</seg>
<seg id="190">There is no lasting added value compared to these additional expenditures of around 10.7 million euros.</seg>
<seg id="191">The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise its specialist supervision for major road construction measures.</seg>
<seg id="192">In this context, it should insist that road construction administrations introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of the cooperation for BRH and NK’ The cooperation met the expectations of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">Both audit institutions developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.</seg>
<seg id="196">It was noted that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadways of the D 8 do not differ from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of both audit institutions involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.</seg>
