<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the Court of Auditors has the power to audit all public finances.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration requires that the courts of auditors have the power to examine tax collection as much as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Organisation of European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The thematic focus of the 6th EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenues by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="7">One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a Court of Auditors is the development of a special strategy for auditing public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which national audit bodies can only carry out their audit activities in cooperation with the audit bodies of other states.</seg>
<seg id="10">As an example, the examination of internationally organised fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many states.</seg>
<seg id="11">Cooperation between the authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.</seg>
<seg id="12">Audit institutions in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">The idea for an audit of the sales tax as well as the system MIAS arose at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.</seg>
<seg id="14">In the course of thorough preparation, the participating audit institutions first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and the procedures of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the evaluation of the available information, we made the selection of the examination subjects for the examination planning.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual states (particularly the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to improving the work of financial management, but can also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Reference number: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of examination:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Management of VAT after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(DE) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">the Commission's audit objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the financial administration in the field of VAT following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter referred to as the "EC") with the free movement of goods and services and the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.</seg>
<seg id="26">(DE) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on mutual assistance in the area of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.</seg>
<seg id="28">VAT Information Exchange System The audits were carried out on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006 jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NK") and the Bundesrech-nungshof ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="29">The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international mutual assistance between the financial administrations as well as the comparison of the VAT management systems in the two states.</seg>
<seg id="30">A joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with European Guideline No. 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI testing standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two courts of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the "exchange of information" priority in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004 of the Commission, other closely related aspects were also examined, such as the registration of taxable persons, tax returns and summary notifications.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation regarding cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) Registration for VAT purposes.</seg>
