<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement of works and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The awarding of services by public authorities is of great importance both for the state and for the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The task of the state is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements when awarding contracts above certain value limits (threshold values).</seg>
<seg id="8">To this end, EU member states have to transpose and apply EU public procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The awarding of services is also an area at risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="12">Due to the generally high damage potential, the contracting authorities must therefore implement appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue benefits when awarding their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits both for the EU-wide award of construction services and for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="14">The main focus of the audits was the application of the EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in construction and road construction or transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">Procurement below the EU thresholds has also been taken into account with a view to preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both audit bodies are summarised in this Joint Report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report should also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Testing areas and verified bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional tests, which he carried out in 2011/2012 with the building authorities, which are responsible for the road construction and the building construction of the federal government in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Audit Office drew on results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from the years 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction work in road construction, railway construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the awarding of federal public contracts is carried out predominantly by the building authorities of the federal states.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for awarding contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In building construction, the awards are carried out decentrally by those bodies that use state budgets.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, freelancers are also involved in sub-areas of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="26">When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and in the market structure for construction services of both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Development of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to the national area are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">In addition, for both EU-wide and national awards, many supplementary individual rules are prescribed by internal administrative provisions;</seg>
<seg id="31">such as the federal government’s so-called “procurement manuals“, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in compliance with public procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the award procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and other statutory provisions that apply both to the area above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Procurement law was substantially amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new regulation increased transparency in the use of public funds, increased competition and limited the possibilities for corruption in the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Principles of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure apply in particular to EU-wide contracts.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are to be applied to the national award types (public tendering, restricted tendering, free-handed procurement), which, however, largely correspond to the above-mentioned EU-wide award types.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (in the case of contracts to be carried out throughout the EU) and the public tender (in the case of national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested company can submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction measure into technical and partial cans.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual awarding of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the aforementioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception here is the simplified procedure, in which a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.</seg>
<seg id="47">Czech public procurement law, in accordance with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including some 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Construction volume of public clients and shares of award types in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 was 307 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this amount, 45.5 billion euros were spent on public construction (15%), which, in addition to federal construction, includes in particular the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The construction volume of the federal government in building construction and highway construction (excluding railway construction and hydraulic engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="54">The volume of contracts for construction work in the federal building and highway construction sector was distributed among the award types in 2011 as follows: 80.7 % open procedures and public tenders, 12.7 % non-open procedures and restricted tenders and 6.6 % negotiation procedures and hands-free contracts.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were Europe-wide awards.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public works in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion euros in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the volume amounted to 7.8 billion euros, which corresponded to 37% of the total construction volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Breakdown by award type for 2011: 65.1% open procedure 14.3% non-public procedure 9.5% negotiation procedure 8.4% simplified procedure for contract volume below the threshold 2.7% other procedure</seg>
<seg id="59">The data relate to all public contracts for deliveries, services and construction services awarded by public contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The o.a. Data show that the parallel audits of both countries focus on a significant part of public procurement, which is of great financial importance for all contracts to be taken into account in the prevention of corruption, and that the open procedure and the public tender are of outstanding importance in the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the results of the parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="62">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel tests in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and on corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="63">In this context, the working groups of both audit institutions compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of construction and road construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">In doing so, they found essentially:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law both in the Czech Republic and in Germany (No. 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">In addition to the EU requirements, the prevention of corruption is also served by the procurement regulations of both countries, which partly differ in their focal points and their detailing (No. 3.2).</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, an essential requirement for the award documents is that they must contain all the information required for the proper preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The service descriptions must be neutral and must not have any competition-restrictive requirements.</seg>
<seg id="69">In Germany, the award documents have largely met these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the object of the order sufficiently.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, construction services must be divided into lots if possible in order to promote competition.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">In its tests, in particular in the field of road construction, the NKO found that the awarding of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots can affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Restrictions on market potential can lead to significant cost increases and entail the risk of price or other agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">Pursuant to the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities may, under certain conditions, agree on additional or amended services with the companies already contracted, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">The respective specifications for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="77">Under the rules of the Czech Republic, contracting authorities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.</seg>
<seg id="78">In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure for EU-wide contracts or the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts, applies.</seg>
<seg id="79">This allows more companies to make offers.</seg>
<seg id="80">This reduces the risk of corruption, complicates price agreements between bidders and leads to the most economic results.</seg>
<seg id="81">For the construction projects, whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded the construction services throughout Europe.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct estimation of the expected order value is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, cost databases are used for the cost assessment of public buildings, especially in building construction,</seg>
<seg id="84">which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">In the case of construction work to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and announcements must be published. This is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to adapt to the planned contracts at an early stage.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the audited building authorities complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or missing controls may have impaired competition (No. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly prone to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of invited applicants must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced beforehand.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries should switch as often as possible among the companies to be invited when selecting applicants.</seg>
<seg id="93">In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed specifications in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited administrations did not take these requirements into account.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of applicants were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, it is necessary to ensure that companies interested in tendering receive the same information during the offer phase in the interest of equal competition.</seg>
<seg id="97">A contact between these companies among themselves and with freelancers who were involved in the creation of the service description is to be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid anticompetitive agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the audited building authorities in Germany partially did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">When opening up the offers in both countries, particular attention must be paid to the multi-eye principle and the principle of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for labelling, documentation, custody and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly well defined in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tests in both countries revealed only a few complaints (No. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by specifications for the structure and process organization.</seg>
<seg id="104">The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting authorities handed over offers for examination to third parties without first reviewing the offers and sufficiently documenting any abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="106">The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (No. 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition are to be informed of the intended award before the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection option also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="109">The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities fail to meet the specified deadlines for the award of contracts or deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content (No. 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible for the audited building authorities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the award notices of some procedures.</seg>
<seg id="113">Also, some of the detected defects diminished the anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Fundamentals of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">EU public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, the principle of competition, the principle of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination, as well as the principle of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">To achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive sets out specific rules for construction works to be awarded across the EU for construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="120">For this purpose, their expected order amounts must reach or exceed a volume of currently 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The rules relate in particular to the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, inter alia for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualification of applicants and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of applicants and bidders.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible violations of public procurement law, the companies concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is understood as the abuse of a position of trust for the private benefit,</seg>
<seg id="128">which is usually initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the European Union, the level of these costs is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">In doing so, they must review the organisation and organisation of their administrations in areas that are particularly at risk of corruption in order to implement appropriate safeguards against corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption – in particular bribery and bribery as well as acceptance and approval of benefits – is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="139">In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a guideline and recommendations on corruption12 prevention in the Federal Administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles must be observed for the award area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eye principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, awarding and settlement, precise and complete documentation of the award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, further anti-corruption requirements have been incorporated into the public procurement regulations.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, for example, the responsible Federal Ministry for Procurement in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system,</seg>
<seg id="142">with the award data - such as the estimated costs and the order amounts - as well as information on the involved freelancers are collected nationwide and evaluated for abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, form the most important basis for preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on anti-corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended therein have already been incorporated into national public procurement law and corresponding administrative provisions around14.</seg>
<seg id="147">The main provisions of the new legislation are as follows: reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to publish the contracts beforehand by the contracting authority, including mention of the reasons for the tender, prohibition of limiting the number of bidders in non-open procedures and thus abolition of the possibility of selecting bidders through lottery procedures, introduction of the obligation to publish the order documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Examination results for the individual phases of the award procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Procurement Documents The Procurement Documents must contain all the information that the bidders need to make an appropriate bid.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the award documents must allow for a correct calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">The bidders may not be transferred any risks that are not calculable for them.</seg>
<seg id="153">The award documents consist in particular of the service description and the contractual conditions.</seg>
<seg id="154">In addition, they contain the requirements for proof of the qualification (fitness) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.</seg>
<seg id="155">Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are directed in particular to the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">In principle, the service description must be product-neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">Avoiding restrictive competition requirements in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the award documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of offers as well as for manipulation in their evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements for technical specifications have been transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">The services are basically product-neutral without factory specifications.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the service descriptions, the individual services must usually be divided into performance units with respective quantity specifications in detail.</seg>
<seg id="166">Prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. B. Euro per m2 or per piece).</seg>
<seg id="167">Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.</seg>
<seg id="168">In any case, the service descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.</seg>
<seg id="169">They must contain precise quantities and must not include services for which it is not clear whether they are needed.</seg>
<seg id="170">Remuneration according to lump sum or time expenditure is to be avoided as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indeterminate requirements in the procurement documents.</seg>
<seg id="172">The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The call for tenders will not be published until the award documents have been completed.</seg>
<seg id="174">Derogations from each other</seg>
<seg id="175">There is no obligation to tender for works in lots in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="176">If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public contracting authorities can divide construction services into several lots.</seg>
<seg id="177">In Germany, construction services are generally divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial lots) and/or by type or subject area (professionals).</seg>
<seg id="178">The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to expand the number of possible providers and to make price agreements more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is generally considered to be the most economical.</seg>
<seg id="180">Criteria for evaluation in the Czech Republic must be stated in the award documents, both in EU-wide and in national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should enable applicants to fully and conclusively identify the criteria according to which their offers are to be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but at the latest in the award documents, is only required in the EU-wide procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="183">In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria must only be set out in an internal administrative award note.</seg>
<seg id="184">Procurement documents, which are prepared by commissioned freelancers, may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or experts in Germany with the building construction and some road construction administrations.</seg>
<seg id="185">The aim is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages through contact with these freelancers without the client's knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send out award documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="187">The contact person for the companies is the client alone.</seg>
<seg id="188">There is currently no provision for this in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="189">Additional or modified services, which prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always required for large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="190">In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of subcontracts to the already contracted company without having to carry out a tendering procedure with public notice.</seg>
<seg id="191">According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services may not exceed half of the main order.</seg>
<seg id="192">In addition, the additional services may not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to the award of such contracts without public notice.</seg>
<seg id="194">However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.</seg>
<seg id="195">If supplementary services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is in principle not possible according to the regulations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="196">In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed must be assumed.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.</seg>
<seg id="198">In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be offset against additional supplementary services.</seg>
<seg id="199">Key audit results</seg>
<seg id="200">BHR</seg>
<seg id="201">Technical specifications and product-neutral tendering</seg>
<seg id="202">In individual cases, the performance descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.</seg>
<seg id="203">Some performance descriptions also contained product-related specifications – for example for graffiti protection, joints or noise protection plates – without this being necessary.</seg>
<seg id="204">In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was considered.</seg>
<seg id="205">Performance directories subdivided by partial services</seg>
<seg id="206">The BRH has not in any of the examined proceedings found violations of the bid to advertise services in principle in a list of services subdivided by partial services.</seg>
<seg id="207">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
<seg id="208">In the vast majority of cases, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="209">In some cases, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the offer phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.</seg>
<seg id="210">Occasionally, the performance directories contained positions where it was not clear whether they were needed.</seg>
<seg id="211">A performance catalogue for demolition work even consisted almost half of such demand positions.</seg>
<seg id="212">Lots and evaluation criteria</seg>
