<seg id="717">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar rules</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the contracting authority has to decide on the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of a proper examination and evaluation of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="722">The client shall place the order within the announced surcharge period,</seg>
<seg id="723">also because the bidders are no longer bound by their offers after the deadline.</seg>
<seg id="724">In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and restricted tenders, the client may not deviate from the content of the offer when concluding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="725">The inferior bidders are to be informed promptly about the award decision and the reasons for not taking their offers into account.</seg>
<seg id="726">Procurement procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, e.g. if the offer prices are excessive or the offers do not meet the requirements of the tender.</seg>
<seg id="727">Derogations from each other</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, there is a 10- or 15-day obligation to provide information and to wait before awarding a contract, even for construction services that are not to be awarded throughout Europe.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, these requirements apply only to the area of EU-wide procurement.</seg>
<seg id="730">In the case of the other proceedings in Germany, the bidders can only be informed of the award decision after the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a tender procedure must be cancelled if only one offer has been received or only one offer could be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only one valuable offer, provided that it complies with the conditions of the tender and is economical.</seg>
<seg id="733">Key audit results</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">In the case of the audited awards, there were only a few complaints at the conclusion of the award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, companies received letters of order for EU-wide contracts before the end of the information periods, which may lead to the invalidity of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">In individual cases, order letters also contained content deviating from the content of the offer, such as changed dates, according to open procedures.</seg>
<seg id="738">In several cases, the contracting authorities did not meet the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In the case of an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract to the second most favourable offer, since a company with a 50% cheaper offer was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the originally offered price after the expiry of the award period.</seg>
<seg id="740">N.K.</seg>
<seg id="741">In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated in terms of content from the bidder's offer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some contracts, e.g. for road maintenance construction measures, for the construction of a motorway and a bypass road, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after the expiry of the statutory period.</seg>
<seg id="743">When awarding construction services for the renovation of former military premises, the contracting authority only forwarded the notification of the award of the contract to all bidders after the expiry of the statutory period.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements to complete the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of the inferior applicants or bidders increases the tools for preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, the deadlines for awarding contracts have been exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In future, the construction authorities should avoid the shortcomings identified in the completion of their procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The award procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings as well as the reasons for the individual decisions.</seg>
<seg id="753">The contracts awarded must be made known in EU-wide procedures.</seg>
<seg id="754">The order data is also recorded in an EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption The documentation of the procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly created documentation enables the traceability of the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders when awarding contracts above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to justify award decisions in detail significantly restricts the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The announcement of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be submitted by the respective contracting authority to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the announcements in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission via the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission compiles an annual EU statistics, through which it can gain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar rules</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed EU legislation on documentation and reporting requirements into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Derogations from each other</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is shortened to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, there is a publication obligation only in the case of restricted tenders and in the case of free-handed contracts from value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without value added tax (so-called "VAT"). Ex-post transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure receive information about the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="772">Key audit results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the audited award procedures were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The award notices did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national regulations.</seg>
<seg id="777">In a tendering procedure, the contracting authority did not justify why it awarded the contract to a company, even though its offer did not contain mandatory evidence.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents of the contracting authorities did not contain all the evidence required for the documentation of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Announcements on the award of orders</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, the contracting authorities failed to make the awarding of contracts known.</seg>
<seg id="781">Further award procedures lacked the evidence that the contracting authorities had made the awarded contracts known.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical listings viewed contained the required minimum information. They had been prepared and dispatched on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex-post transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the audited building authorities published the order data of the completed procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">However, a construction administration did not publish this data due to a transmission error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The building administration noticed this mistake only after half a year,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the order data of the procurement procedures completed up to that time have not been published.</seg>
<seg id="789">N.K.</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In the case of construction measures for the organisation of a major sporting event, the documentation of the award procedures showed considerable shortcomings. These were mainly inaccurate information, such as incorrect offer prices in the minutes of the valuation commissions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some minutes of the offer openings were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Announcements on the award of orders</seg>
<seg id="794">In the case of several road construction projects, notices of contracts awarded were published only belatedly or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The rules on documentation and reporting and reporting obligations are broadly consistent in both countries and implement EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">The transparency of the procurement procedures, including the award of contracts, is thus guaranteed in principle.</seg>
<seg id="798">The rules to be applied in the Czech Republic for publication go a little further than the requirements in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The shortcomings in the documentation and in the announcements shown limited the orruption-preventive effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">The building authorities should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and assignments and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits carried out by the NCA and the BRH have focused on two main areas that are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works by public authorities: the application of EU public procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law will allow cross-border competition to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures not only serve to prevent or at least reduce corruption. They should also avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two audit bodies on the application of the public procurement rules in both countries and the comparison of these regulations provide information on similarities and differences, which can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU public procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed the EU's requirements for the award of construction services into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of works and the consideration of the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the companies involved and transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The building authorities of both countries have partly backed these bids very extensively by further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has also largely transferred the requirements for the construction services to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the investigations carried out by the Court of Auditors have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The building administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the complaints raised when implementing the EU regulations.</seg>
<seg id="814">In particular, the audits in the Czech Republic have identified risks that affect the cost-effectiveness of the awards.</seg>
<seg id="815">For example, incomplete service descriptions necessitated additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation. In addition, the cost assessments were usually insufficiently prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the transport sector.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations have not had the aim of uncovering cases of corruption,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the Court of Auditors does not have the appropriate instruments for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of works and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">In preventing corruption, both countries have set different priorities.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition as well as transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their specific requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the relevant regulations specify very precisely how the bids for the prevention of corruption must be taken into account in the course of the award procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">The BRH considers, in particular, that the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tendering is a suitable instrument for significantly reducing the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative intervention.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures as well as various organizational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no need for fundamental changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations in the award of construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The anti-corruption rules are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some of the benchmarks.</seg>
<seg id="832">The building authorities should continue to train their employees on the requirements for corruption prevention and make them even more aware of this problem.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, without controls and sufficient safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Therefore, manipulation and corruption-prone tasks should only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.</seg>
<seg id="836">N.K.</seg>
<seg id="837">The Czech Republic adopted at government level a strategy against corruption, in which the area of public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The examinations of the NCD took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, since the contracting authorities must justify the profitability of the award of contracts, the calculation of the expected prices, the appropriateness of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations and must properly document and publish all these aspects.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">In principle, the NCC and the BRH rate the implementation of the EU requirements positively.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's rules on competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and ideal damage potential caused by manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both courts of auditors see the construction authorities in their countries as being required to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a favourable effect on supply prices, provided that this leads to greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient awarding of contracts by public authorities.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialized building authorities. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks – with the exception of transport construction projects – are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">The Court of Auditors of both countries has the intention, even after the completion of their joint project, to further develop the relevant findings for them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both audit institutions are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out above are of general importance in order to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the economic award of works in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
<seg id="853">Annexes</seg>
</p>
