<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="3">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">A focus of the Court of Auditors' activities should therefore be on the audit of this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone causes annual tax losses in the European Union of an estimated EUR 100 billion1.</seg>
<seg id="8">Already at the 6th EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed out the need for increased cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This makes it possible for the Court of Auditors, e.g. Exchange examination approaches and optimise the examination practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation, as it is harmonised within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, for the first time, the courts of auditors of both countries conducted parallel audits in the area of the USt.</seg>
<seg id="12">The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since USt fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the courts of auditors is needed. This allows a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively countering the USt fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two audit bodies decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Examination number:(CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of the USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as NKx), audit</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the audit is to:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The USt administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities in intergovernmental mutual assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the audit bodies.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, further examination fields - linked to the USt - should be processed.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings should be compared in order to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.</seg>
<seg id="23">The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008 including relevant information from the period before the examination period up to the conclusion of the examination.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination</seg>
<seg id="25">The courts of auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on an audit for the administration of the USt.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel examination, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,</seg>
<seg id="27">which made a re-examination purpose appear.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, the two Court of Auditors issued recommendations for the administration of the USt.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the identified suspected cases should be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination also dealt with other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of USt claims and the USt audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Court of Auditors found that:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit</seg>
<seg id="33">Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxable persons should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for the USt in the two states and found differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxable persons within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the existing databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of USt persons.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxable persons and their possible deletion.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree, in accordance with their decision in principle, on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the USt system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the final version of the draft.</seg>
<seg id="41">The above-mentioned common rules are no longer included. The two Court of Auditors regret this.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary notifications As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended that Member States submit summary notifications (CMs) on a monthly basis in the future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed more closely.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax (VAT) for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has shortened the deadline for the surrender of the ZM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the USt Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010. It has thus failed to transpose the obligation to submit the ZM monthly into national law on time.</seg>
<seg id="48">Recommendation 3: Data synchronisation of USt pre-registrations and ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of procedures for USt pre-registrations and ZM The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Audit Office will monitor the further development.</seg>
<seg id="51">Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two audit bodies agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Audit Office focused on the German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management".</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">At the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or those of the taxable persons of the two states in the USt pre-registrations (or. USt declarations) or ZM had been explained differently.</seg>
<seg id="58">The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between CZ and Germany for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective financial administrations had taken appropriate measures to this end (e.g. subsequent USt fixes or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community sales</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between taxable persons in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify taxable persons at risk.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the point of view of an active participating state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German USt-ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU found both normal business transactions and those suspected of USt fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected sales.</seg>
<seg id="69">The FÄ were only able to examine sales with high risk to a limited extent. This was particularly true for so-called "missing traders", whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to be able to prove fraud to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">Suspicion of carousel fraud in imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">it is advisable for customs and tax authorities to work more closely together in order to be able to track the originality of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET because they do not believe that there is a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Bundesrechnungshof found that the German tax administration uses other instruments to identify taxable persons at risk.</seg>
<seg id="74">However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation:</seg>
<seg id="76">was created by the EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network for combating USt fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are dealt with in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">Bundesrechnungshof and NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">These statistics contained inconsistencies.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two Court of Auditors consider it useful to re-discuss statistics at EU level in order to avoid any remaining inconsistencies in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should contain more information about the USt.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat USt fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both audit institutions believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Commission should support the Member States in this, if desired.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. USt testing at large companies</seg>
<seg id="90">The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the USt audit of large companies in both states.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from the financial administrations with a questionnaire, which they considered important in this context.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the situation in both countries is different.</seg>
<seg id="93">CZ has a system for selecting risky cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on USt audits, balance sheet data, and profit and loss statements).</seg>
<seg id="94">As a result, the USt control can be effectively controlled and analyzed overall.</seg>
<seg id="95">A special finance office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">Germany does not yet have a comparable system. This complicates the control and analysis of the USt control as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German financial administration concentrates more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the USt pre-registrations or USt declarations and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Examination procedure</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Examination procedure in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Division II - Government Budget Revenues as well as the Regional Departments I-Pilsen, I-Eesk-Budjovice, xiii Brno and xv Ostrava audited in the period May 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">Certified bodies were the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 FÄ: Tax Office (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Beclav, FA in Doma-lice, FA in Hodon-n, FA in Hradec Kr-lov, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA in Ostrava, FA in</seg>
<seg id="103">The Senate of the Czech Court of Auditors approved the audit findings on 27 April 2010.</seg>
