<seg id="548">i.e. the audit covers all relevant taxes, i.e. income tax, corporation tax, commercial tax and VAT.</seg>
<seg id="549">The sales tax can be audited either by auditors or USt special auditors.</seg>
<seg id="550">Practice varies and depends on the administrative structure of the individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="551">The number of tax periods covered by an audit usually varies between three and five years.</seg>
<seg id="552">The BpO 2000 assumes three years.</seg>
<seg id="553">The audit is subject to all taxes to which a company has been charged.</seg>
<seg id="554">4.5.3 Management of the VAT audit at large companies</seg>
<seg id="555">In accordance with the agreement, both courts of auditors did not examine individual cases. They looked into the question of how the financial administrations proceed in the USt audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="556">With the help of a questionnaire, they collected information from the financial administrations that is essential for the audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="557">What statistical records and evaluations for the USt testing of large companies are available to the management of the tax administration?</seg>
<seg id="558">In particular:</seg>
<seg id="559">Are there statistics or records on the extent to which a distinction is made between USt fraud control and general USt testing?</seg>
<seg id="560">CZ: No, the current version of the ATIS system does not allow such a distinction.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The financial administration does not distinguish between audits to combat USt fraud and general USt audits.</seg>
<seg id="562">Are there statistics or records on the timeliness of the tests?</seg>
<seg id="563">CZ: Information on the timeliness of audits of intra-Community acquisitions of selected USt-mandators is recorded in the ATIS system;</seg>
<seg id="564">The same applies to information about the beginning and end of the examination of the FA.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the statistics for auditors summarised at federal level only contain information about the so-called average last audit period (year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This figure does not give an overview of the audit periods selected for individual companies.</seg>
<seg id="567">USt special auditors focus on the last USt investment periods and are also authorized to audit large companies.</seg>
<seg id="568">The federal statistics for USt special auditors do not contain any information on the size class of the audited company.</seg>
<seg id="569">There are statistics or records on the nature of the surplus result; e.g. B. subdivided by:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. real additional result (e.g. B. Application of a reduced rate instead of the general rate of VAT)</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. Incorrect surplus result (e.g. B. Relocation/shifting of a matter not objectionable under VAT law to another tax period)</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. Cash effectiveness (payment of the fixed additional result)</seg>
<seg id="573">CZ:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech tax administration monitors the number of tax audits carried out, the amount of the additional tax result broken down by type of tax, the number of taxable persons audited and the number of tax periods audited.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (on-the-spot investigations, dunning procedures) are monitored in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">Irrespective of this, the amount of additional payments and the receipts of payments are recorded.</seg>
<seg id="577">Statistics on tax liabilities are broken down by type of tax. However, no distinction is made between tax liabilities arising from a tax return and those arising from the audit activities of the FA.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the statistics compiled at federal level for auditors and USt special auditors do not differ according to the above-mentioned criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">Nor did most financial authorities, where local surveys were carried out, differentiate in this respect.</seg>
<seg id="580">- Are there any fields of examination that are likely to yield results?</seg>
<seg id="581">CZ: Yes, the FA can select test cases based on criteria associated with selected key figures stored in the ATIS system.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at federal level for auditors and USt special auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, the federal and state finance ministries have agreed on a common approach.</seg>
<seg id="585">Accordingly, auditors and tax investigators of the countries have to enter the additional tax result they have achieved if a certain threshold value is exceeded in ZAUBER.</seg>
<seg id="586">In this case, additional information must be provided, e.g. on the origin of the USt surplus result achieved.</seg>
<seg id="587">What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">CZ:</seg>
<seg id="589">- Large taxable companies have unlawfully used input tax deduction for purchased deliveries and services,</seg>
<seg id="590">- which were not used for an entrepreneurial activity in accordance with Section 72 (1) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="591">- which were used for representation expenses in accordance with Section 75 (3) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="592">due to invoices that do not comply with the requirements of Section 73 (1) CZ UStG</seg>
<seg id="593">- Large taxable enterprises have omitted the registration of USt to be paid as provided for in Section 21 (1) CZ UStG.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at federal level for auditors and USt special auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings on the USt from audits of large companies are not recorded separately by the countries.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, the Federal Central Tax Office can evaluate the database ZAUBER, into which auditors and tax investigators of the Länder have to enter the additional tax result they have achieved if a certain threshold is exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="598">- Does the financial administration analyze areas of audit that are likely to yield results and draw consequences for strategic management?</seg>
<seg id="599">CZ: Yes, for example, nationwide tests are carried out with regard to risky goods and industries.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and USt special auditors do not provide any information on particularly "energy-based" audit fields.</seg>
<seg id="602">With regard to the analysis of such information, the benefits and the way in which it is used further, there were different views among the survey bodies.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some senior financial directorates provide such information to the FÄ, but the FÄ is free to use it or not.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">As a result, large amounts of information are processed automatically in the CZ. Among other things, data from USt audits, as well as key figures from balance sheets, profit and loss statements are processed in the system.</seg>
<seg id="606">CZ is able to control the selection of high-risk cases based on a wide range of information.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the evaluation and management of USt tests in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In the CZ, the establishment of a special finance office for large enterprises is planned for 2012.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the financial administration does not collect comparable amounts of data.</seg>
<seg id="610">Accordingly, it is more difficult to perform these tasks in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="611">The emphasis is more on the selection of relevant individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="612">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of the information in USt pre-registrations or USt declarations as well as test notices, qualified examiners select the cases to be examined and ensure the applicable taxation.</seg>
<seg id="614">Suitable management processes and risk management systems must be introduced in order to reduce revenue losses at the USt and at the same time increase the risk of being discovered for unreliable entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="615">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="616">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two audit institutions has proved its worth.</seg>
<seg id="619">In this way, necessary insights into the systems used in both countries could be gained: This applies in particular to: - intra-Community sales, - risk management at USt, in particular with regard to the selection of risky sales, - recovery of USt claims and - USt testing of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in the strategies for detecting USt fraud and in the systems described above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion among interested parties on which audit approaches and strategies can be used to combat fraud. This applies, for example, to the relationship within and between the Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and insights gained should encourage us to continue to jointly examine the administration of the USt in the future.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. Kommunique</seg>
<seg id="625">The report has been prepared in Czech, English and German and signed by the Presidents of the Czech Court of Auditors and the Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="626">Status of information: June 2010.</seg>
